title: For Sale:  Korea Era IR M3 Sniper scope
location: NW Suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale and maybe partial trade is my Korea Era Us military Sniper Scope. Known officially as: M3, sniperscope, infrared, set no. 1, 20,000 volts. Made by american optical co. Buffalo, NY 6-23-51. Made to be mounted on a special M1 carbine known as the M2 carbine making the whole setup a M3. 

Very good condition. Really nice for how old it is. How does it compare to others? I don't know. I've never seen one that wasn't in a book or on the internet. This is the only one I have ever seen. Very rare, very cool piece of American Military History.

What is there and what isn't. This comes with the IR scope, IR Light, Foregrip/ Handle with the trigger, power transformer box, all necessary original wiring, 1 tube, original rubberized backpack(nice), and original chest. As far as what is missing? I'm really no expert but I think there was a tool set and more tubes. These are not there. And of course no .30 carbine. No rust anywhere and looks to be the original finish. Some scratches on the scope but not bad. A little corrosion on a small copper piece behind the light source. And it looks like the red filter is a little rough. The outside plastic of the light source is fine, its the red filter inside. I have not taken this apart or tried to clean any of it. 

Because this is so rare I did not want auction it, I wanted a lot of people to have a shot at owning it. Same with gun broker. I found it in Mn I would like a collector in MN to give it a good home. So I figured the only fair way to do it wold be to take offers. So, if you want it, take a shot at it and email me your best offer. If you know what it is, you know what its worth, and how often you can find one.

As far as trades go... I might, might, take one of the following as partial trade with cash. 1. Ruger .44 carbine semi-auto. Prefer older tube fed. 2. Ruger No. 1 in 270 win, 280 rem, 30.06 or 303 brit. 3. HK usp Tactical all black. Of course these guns must be nice.

Of course all cash is always nice. FTF meet. Leave your name and number or I will not get back to you.

Thanks for looking.

First is A 1907 Australian Bayonet. Fits the British rifles of the ww1 era. Original leather/metal sheath. Push button attachment still works. excellent condition. Better condition than any I've ever seen online. 


The second is A WW2 German Nazi army Officer's Dagger. Ivory handle, original metal sheath and all engravings intact. Has original belt loop up top, not on bottom. Handle is cracked and chipped, and blade is in great shape. Was denazified, meaning the swastika was taken off the bottom of the war eagle on the hilt. Probably done before it was brought back to the US. Pretty good shape overall. Very rare. Ivory handle is usually associated with higher ranks, much rarer than the similar plastic handled daggers. this one is dated between 1936-1938 I believe. 

I'm open to trades or cash. I'm not gonna put a dollar amount, do research and make a fair cash offer. 

Trade offers considered

title: For Sale:  Kahr PM9 w/ External Safety
postcontent:
NIB
Taxes will be included for Iowa residents
No low ball offers and willing to accept trades for pistols.



Loaded Chamber Indicator
This model is designed to provide physical indication if there is a bullet loaded in the chamber. The product is designed with a lever mounted on the top of the slide. The lever is marked as Indicator in red lettering. When a bullet is chambered it pushes the lever upward and out of position. The operator will visually see the lever as it is raised up. Also the operator will be able to feel the indicator as being out of its normal resting position as it will not be flush with the top of the slide, thus warning the operator that the firearm is loaded.

Enhanced Trigger
Kahr’s new enhanced trigger will be featured on Kahr models with external safeties and loaded chamber indicators. The enhanced trigger has a shorter length of pull compared to the Kahr standard trigger. The new enhanced trigger has a 1/4” length of pull with an approximate 7.5 lb. trigger pull weight compared to a 3/8” length of pull for the standard trigger. The trigger pull weight for the enhanced trigger is the same as the standard trigger, approximately 7.5 lb. 

External Safety
This model has, in addition to the internal safety, an external safety that will prevent the firearm from firing when the safety is in the safe position. The product has an external lever with two settings. When the lever is pushed completely up and the red dot is fully visible, the firearm is in the armed position and ready to fire with the pull of the trigger. When the lever is pushed down, and the red dot is hidden the firearm is in the safe position and will not function with the pull of the trigger. The safety works in the following manner. When the lever is in the down (Safe) position the connecting cam on the lever pushes the trigger bar out of position, disconnecting it from the cocking cam. If the trigger is pulled in the safe mode, the cocking cam will not release the striker and the firearm will not fire. When the lever is pushed up (Fire/Armed position) the cam moves out of place and the trigger bar moves up, again connecting with the cocking cam. The firearm is then ready to fire with the pull of the trigger.
